Text.Value: As you wish. Better I impart the knowledge to you now, in case I fall trying to defend the grove.
I cannot allow these butchers to threaten my grove. The natural order must be protected.

EditorData.AnimationTags: CDavis: If not in VO use gesture constructions.
EditorData.NodeContext: Practical. No lover of violence, but knows when needs must. Gestures at the surrounds on 'these butchers' to refer to the goblins and their allies.

Text.Value: Follow me.
The other druids are dead, by my hand.
A drow forced me to defend myself. Afterwards, I was able to study the parasite that slithered out of the corpse, see what drives these 'True Souls'.
Best if I try settle this discreetly - wait here, and you'll have your deaths.
Look around you - there's no order anymore. Only chaos.
I could come and help you... but be warned - I won't be able to suppress my animal side. Subtlety will not be an option.
Aradin and his lot were looking for a way down there - they were promised riches if they retrieved a relic called the Nightsong. But I think there's more.
I found the hidden entrance in the temple of Selûne - the way is clear.
Come with me. I could use your help.
I'll remain here and do what I can to disrupt these cultists' plans. Perhaps I can stop their attack before it's even launched. Farewell.
But the grove must come first, I'm afraid.
You did...? Nature's found a most furious defender in you.

EditorData.NodeContext: Surprised and impressed. The player has fulfilled a mission before he could issue it.

Text.Value: Then the grove is doomed, and perhaps you as well.

EditorData.NodeContext: Disappointed but dignified

Text.Value: You aided a bear without knowing if it would savage you? A true friend of nature - or perhaps a lunatic.

EditorData.NodeContext: Curious

Text.Value: By all means - pursue any leads you may have. But I sense all roads will lead to Moonrise.
From this stronghold, Ketheric's forces could access both the temple of Selûne and Moonrise Towers - but he was defeated before he could launch an attack.

EditorData.NodeContext: seh-LOON-eh

Text.Value: Leave.
I'll need that luck, along with all the Oak Father's blessings.
Not all drow are as you say.
Altered parasites? A cure at Moonrise Towers, maybe? Sounds like guesswork at best.
The grove is lost to me. To everyone. It's useless for me to stay here... there's nothing left to fight for.

EditorData.NodeContext: The fight goes out of him.

Text.Value: We're done here. I'll be on my way.
If I join you, we'll likely have to slaughter this entire place. You may want to use discretion when approaching the goblin leaders.

EditorData.NodeContext: A warning of sorts - he doesn't want to be a liability.

Text.Value: Be warned - my presence could make things more difficult... I can only restrain my bear form so much. I won't be able to help but attack goblins.

EditorData.NodeContext: A warning of sorts - he doesn't want to be a liability.

Text.Value: You should get out of here. It's not safe.
This magic you mentioned - it isn't normal for these parasites?
I'm sorry I can't do more. Thank you, and good luck with the grove.
I helped overthrow Ketheric Thorm and his Dark Justiciars years ago. But I failed to prevent him from unleashing darkness across the region before he was defeated.
Where are you going? We have work to do - enemies to kill.

EditorData.logicalname: Player trying to leave region/didn't refuse to help

Text.Value: I'm certain. The Underdark is dangerous, yes, but the alternative is suicide. Be patient and be thorough - the path will reveal itself in time.
Innocents go in, True Souls come out. Given that all of these True Souls are infected, it has to be the source of this magic.
Already...? If only I'd gone with you instead of Aradin.
Unfair of me, perhaps, but I've had few encounters with drow to make me think otherwise.

EditorData.NodeContext: 'Prove me wrong. Save the innocents at the grove'

Text.Value: I know the Underdark - it's lethal. I'll travel overland.
Killing's never my first choice, but those three were too dangerous to leave alive.
I can't stop you, in fact. Which brings me to my next problem...

EditorData.NodeContext: Some hesitance in the second sentence. He's about to segue into asking a favour

Text.Value: Precisely. Then perhaps I could have done something about both the shadow curse and ceremorphosis aberrations.
There is no safety. Not while this rot festers. Once it is cut out - once the grove is secure - then I shall leave.

EditorData.NodeContext: Emphatic

Text.Value: Hurry, then. I will meet you there.
Leave.
This is different. There's more fingers on a hand than there are survivors of that place.

EditorData.NodeContext: Deadly serious and speaking from personal experience, The place he's talking about is no joke.

Text.Value: Just the information, please.
You owe more than thanks, I think.
Glad I could be of help.
Say I decide to try this Underdark route after all - how do I get started?
Well, consider me introduced. And consider me grateful.

EditorData.NodeContext: Humble and grateful

Text.Value: Thank you. I know it's a great deal to ask, but the grove is everything to me.
And you'll receive it soon enough. Return to the grove; I'll make my own way there.
So all of this was for nothing.
Perhaps you can enlighten me.

EditorData.NodeContext: 'Prove me wrong. Save the innocents at the grove'

Text.Value: Hmmm... that looks very alien. As alien as the mind flayers. They do not belong on this world.
You rabid dog. Murderer! Those were the servants of Silvanus - nature's guardians!

EditorData.NodeContext: Incandescent with anger. Can hardly believe what he's hearing.

Text.Value: Tread carefully. You're on the right track, I'm sure - but there'll still be danger and difficulty before you reach Moonrise.
So how do I find this underground route?
This will have to wait for now.
It's too late to merely kill this horde's leadership - their forces are already marching. If you want me to help, you need to help me first.
Follow me, then. Your bear form may prove useful.
Rare is the beast that survives decapitation. Help me eliminate the drow Minthara, the hobgoblin Dror Ragzlin, and that perversion of a priestess, Gut.

EditorData.NodeContext: Giving a list of targets in exchange for his help. D-Roar Rags-lin, Min-Thara

Text.Value: Nature's blessings. Are you ready to do what is necessary?

EditorData.logicalname: Player didn't refuse to help/ left Halsin behind

Text.Value: I found an elevator - but it leads right into the shadow curse.

EditorData.InternalNodeContext: This node if the player clicked the elevator from Grymforge to SCL

Text.Value: Leave.
...Hrrm. That look in your eyes - I've seen it before. Are you feeling all right?

EditorData.NodeContext: switching subject, realizing there is something wrong with you

Text.Value: I've been to the Emerald Grove. It's in grave danger, it sorrows me to say.
I've been to the Emerald Grove. It's in danger.
I didn't find what I came here for - a way to remove the tadpoles - but I found the next best thing. I found out where they come from.
You seem to know a lot about this. Will you come with me to Moonrise?
I'm as certain as I can be. If you have a better alternative, I won't stop you.
Very well, but no witnesses can survive. We will kill this whole camp together.
I never thought I'd say this, but it sounds like the Underdark is the safer route.
The bear is a noble beast. I will not fear it, or abandon it.
Nature's bounty to you, brother. But I must admit I have not heard of you.
Haven't heard of you.
They left me no choice. I had to defend myself.
Come with me.
Someone is using very powerful magic to modify these tadpoles. They are using them to exert control over the infected.
I'll pray to Silvanus that you have a change of heart. But time is short.

EditorData.NodeContext: Disappointed but dignified

Text.Value: I overheard that the cultists are sending all of their captives to Moonrise Towers.
Perhaps... but I wouldn't want to place all my faith in blind luck.
The grove is counting on us.
You could also go under. There is a tunnel somewhere in this very temple of Selûne. It leads to Moonrise Towers through the Underdark.

EditorData.NodeContext: seh-LOON-eh

Text.Value: What would you do?
How did you come to study mind flayer parasites?
No, that's not right - praise you, my friend. The grove owes you a debt beyond measure.

EditorData.NodeContext: Sincerely grateful

Text.Value: It may prove impossible to avoid the shadow curse entirely, but if you find any way to limit your exposure, seize it.

EditorData.InternalNodeContext: GLO_Halsin_AcknowledgedGrymforge sets whenever the player enquires about the Grymforge and Halsin acknowledges how it may relate to the journey to Moonrise.

Text.Value: You will not see another day.

EditorData.NodeContext: A cold, furious hiss. Combat breaks out immediately afterwards.

Text.Value: And you... the way you speak... you're worse than the Absolutists here. At least they live with the pretence of purpose.
What should I do?
All the leaders are dead - the grove's safe.
I've done my part - now tell me about Moonrise.
Wait - I could help you find a cure... but I need to settle matters here first.
It's who I am, who my mind makes me: a killer.
May Silvanus guide us.
Gladly, but first I must return to the grove. As you made short work of the goblins' leaders, there's nothing stopping me. Come join me in your own time.
Long ago, a man called Ketheric Thorm built a secret stronghold deep down there, before rallying a whole army of Dark Justiciars - Shar worshippers.

EditorData.NodeContext: Kether-ick Thor-m

Text.Value: Help me kill the leaders of this horde, save my grove. Then I will help you.

EditorData.NodeContext: Practical. No lover of violence, but knows when needs must.

Text.Value: Thank me not, the slaughter was a pleasure.
Stay here.
Very well. Return to the grove. I'll make my own way there - then we can see about this parasite of yours.
You sound all but deranged by blood, but I suppose even a feral wolf has a caring hound at heart.
I cannot come with you, though I wish I could. At least let me tell you what I know; help you on your journey.
Of course. Let's focus on that.
So it seems, though I don't know how. You will have to choose your approach carefully.
Either way, I owe thanks. I am the druid Halsin.
I'll make my way to the grove - join me there.
Don't make it sound so tempting. I already know you'd rather I stayed and helped you.
It seems the Absolute's forces are already marching on the grove. I'll have to try get ahead of them, do what I can.
The ringleaders have to die. The very natural order of things is in danger, thanks to them.

EditorData.logicalname: He wants you to kill leaders/player didn't refuse

Text.Value: Travelling to Moonrise is no small task. Expect dangers like you've never seen before.
I spoke to Nettie - she said you could help me with the parasite in my head.
I do want you to help me, yes. But I am not exaggerating.
What...? How? Why?! Explain yourself at once!

EditorData.NodeContext: Shocked and angry.

Text.Value: I escaped from an illithid ship after being infected. Maybe the process was interrupted.
Indeed? Not the most opportune moment, but given the lengths you went to, I assume there's some urgency.

EditorData.NodeContext: Professional interest piqued.

Text.Value: How do I find this passage through the Underdark?
Come on then, what's the problem? Unless you'd rather wait for an audience of goblins.
Nature speaks to me. Birds report what they've seen. And I've overheard goblins speaking of it, too. Moonrise is at the heart of all this, I'm sure of it.
I had no idea anyone beyond their ranks was infected. You have my sincere sympathies.
Parasite in your head...? You mean you have one of them?
Impressive healing skills. I need the help of someone like you.

EditorData.InternalNodeContext: Halsin cast a healing spell on himself before this dialogue bagan, If the player doesn't know who he is, this is the reasoning for them asking him to help them.

Text.Value: You may reconsider once you see the effects of the curse for yourself.
I told you, nowhere is safe. Not while this rot festers. Once it is cut out - once the grove is secure - then I shall leave.

EditorData.NodeContext: Emphatic

EditorData.logicalname: Alias - No Grove Return, Leaders Dead

Text.Value: Not only do you speak with a bear, but you free it, too? A true friend of nature - or perhaps a lunatic.

EditorData.NodeContext: Curious

Text.Value: That sounds like what you need. But the next part of the journey mightn't be straightforward - or safe.
Any who linger are twisted by the curse; they become shadow beings - tormented, dangerous souls.
Sympathies won't help me to survive.
At least tell me what you know about Moonrise. You owe me, after all.
Leave.
This curse shrouds everything in shadow - you will not find life, light, or anything natural there.
Ah. Lunatic, then.

EditorData.NodeContext: Deadpan joke

Text.Value: What business do you have at Moonrise? You said you'd go there, if you could.
My thanks. If you prevail, I'll owe you the debt of a lifetime.

EditorData.NodeContext: Sincere.

Text.Value: A dwarf called Brian, I believe. Though there's no guarantee that the goblins left him recognisable.
Danger. Are you sure that's the best way to Moonrise?
I've heard you're an unmatched healer. I need your help.
The Absolute's forces can tolerate such a place?
You've already been? Impressive. You'll make me redundant at this rate. What did you find?

EditorData.NodeContext: Impressed and a little amused at the player's diligence (finding a place before he can even tell them about it)

Text.Value: I can see to some matters there, and we can discuss what comes next amidst more... bucolic surroundings than here.

EditorData.NodeContext: Halsin would very much like to leave the grim dungeon and go back to his grove.

Text.Value: They are the ones holding these parasites together. Remove them and nature will cure itself.

EditorData.NodeContext: Practical. No lover of violence, but knows when needs must.

Text.Value: Then everything we did here was hopeless.
You learned all this from your studies?
Very well. My claws are yours.
To get to the Towers, you'll need to pass through a terrible place - a cursed place.
You know what's needed - the deaths of Dror Ragzlin, the drow Minthara, and the priestess, Gut. May nature guide you.
You will? Oak Father bless you. I'll be in your debt twice over if we succeed.
Keep looking. If they're present, then it's likely there's a route to Moonrise somewhere.
All right. How do I help?
Tell me, then. I'm going to do whatever it takes.

EditorData.AnimationTags: [REUSE] HALSIN raises his hand to the player's head (no contact) and pulls it away once realizing what he senses [CodyM]
EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Halsin raises a hand to your head, magically connecting with you (no contact). He gives an alarmed look - he knows what’s inside you

Text.Value: But in my eagerness, I put far too much faith in the abilities of Aradin and his band. We didn't even get close.
I understand. You've done far more than most have for the grove, just by freeing me.

EditorData.NodeContext: Stiff upper lip. He's crushed that the player won't help, but he maintains dignity

Text.Value: Absolute followers - but that's about all.

EditorData.InternalNodeContext: This node if the player didn't click the elevator from Grymforge to SCL

Text.Value: A jest - I truly am grateful. If only I could repay you.
I need your help.
Very well. I'll go rescue the grove.
You'll need to pick up where Aradin left off - find the hidden entrance. It's somewhere in these ruins, from what I've heard.
But there are other matters to attend to before that.
I'm not much of a hero... those I look after seem to end up dead.

EditorData.logicalname: KILLED ALFIRA + WAS NICE TO HER

Text.Value: You did it. You actually did it! The leaders dead - praise Silvanus.

EditorData.InternalNodeContext: Disable his dialogue, he then disappears, appears in the Grove and gets a new dialogue
EditorData.NodeContext: Jubilant. The leaders of the horde threatening his home have been eliminated.

Text.Value: Kagha... I should have suspected she'd take things too far. I'll deal with her when I can.

EditorData.NodeContext: Displeased yet not entirely surprised. He's going to read Kagha the riot act if he lives long enough to do so.

Text.Value: There must be another way to cure myself - my kin have dealt with these parasites before.
There must be another way to cure myself.
I'll wait here. Just know that you're gambling with the grove's very existence.
Oh, I'm quite aware of that, rest assured - but where is safe right now?

EditorData.NodeContext: Rhetorical

Text.Value: Not that I'm eager to try stopping you, given the short work you made of the leadership here. With them dead, it's high time I got back to the grove.
Return to the grove; I'll make my own way there.
No, this is different. Altered. The magic used is beyond me... it's either not of this world, or so ancient as to be lost to even nature's memory.
I'm something of an expert when it comes to imperilling myself.
I think this artefact has something to do with it.
I don't know. Ketheric's followers were defeated or vanished before the effects of the curse took hold.
Anything is preferable to risking the shadow curse.
There's no pretence in not wanting to play the assassin. You're on your own.
I've no right to ask more of you... but if you could help me, I'd be free to join your journey to Moonrise.

EditorData.NodeContext: A touch sheepish. We've just freed him, and now he finds he has to ask another favour.

Text.Value: You could go overland - along the Risen Road or through the mountains. Easier at first, but you'll run into the shadow curse eventually.
You drow relish turning on your own, if there's something to be gained. Don't pretend otherwise.

EditorData.NodeContext: Speaking to a drow - 'please, don't pretend to be a bleeding heart' (prejudiced, but a common and often correct assessment of drow)

Text.Value: Kagha is dead. She was swayed by Shadow Druids. I had no choice.
Indeed. After we dealt with the drow that ambushed us, Nettie and I were able to inspect the corpse - and the creature that slithered out of it.
May Silvanus guide your hand. Focus on the leaders - that's all it will take to restore the balance here.
Is that why you went with Aradin? You thought he might uncover this route to Moonrise?
Gladly, but I have some matters to settle first. You go ahead - I'll join you at your camp.
Sounds like I've no choice - I need to find a way through.
This shadow curse - does it affect Shar worshippers?
If you want to find a cure, you must head there and discover how the tadpoles are being manipulated.
My business there began long ago, and has led to a lifetime of regret.
Having a shapeshifting bear-druid at my side might make things easier.
Oh, certainly. But I live modestly at the best of times, and this is far from the best of times.

EditorData.NodeContext: 'Do I look like I have any gold to pay you?'

Text.Value: You must get ahead of them, muster the defences.

EditorData.NodeContext: The player's mission

Text.Value: If I could join you and get close to Moonrise, perhaps I could have both helped you find a cure for your infection and lifted the curse.
Dark Justiciars? I must see for myself.
That must be where these enchantments are placed on them, and it's where you'll find your cure.
Doubtful - I already killed the goblin leadership.
Are these Sharrans still to be found?
If you should have a chance to strike down the leaders of this horde, the world will be a better place for it. Farewell.

EditorData.InternalNodeContext: Halsin to go off stage and reappear at the player camp. (New flag needed)
EditorData.NodeContext: Halsin leaves after this to process what's happened. He'll later reappear at the player's campsite.

Text.Value: How are you so sure Moonrise is where I have to go?
The Underdark's my home. Better to take that route than risk this curse.
Then... then it is as you say. They forgot their principles; you had no choice. I will mourn them when I can.

EditorData.NodeContext: Processing the loss of his comrades, yet he knows they were in the wrong.  He bears no ill will to the player and doesn't have time to truly mourn while his mission is still ongoing

Text.Value: The grove isn't my problem. I have to concentrate on saving myself.
How is this possible...?

EditorData.NodeContext: Wondering out loud.

Text.Value: I can't help you. I just need you to tell me about Moonrise Towers.
Oak Father preserve you, child... You're infected, aren't you? The mind flayers' spawn.

EditorData.NodeContext: Hushed, grave

Text.Value: I have some matters to settle, then I'll join you at your camp. There, we can talk properly.
You weren't speaking lightly when you said you needed help. Let me tell you what I know.

EditorData.NodeContext: Understatement of the century

Text.Value: I don't know.
That's true, I won't lie. But I won't let you march towards Moonrise without knowing what you'd face.
As bones, perhaps. But their hidden structures might still remain.
Wait. Now that the goblins' leaders are dead, I could join you - help you find a cure. I just need to make arrangements back at the grove. Find me there, if you wish.
I spent years researching the curse, trying to put an end to it. Nothing has worked - yet.
I am aware. I foolishly left it vulnerable to this rabble. There's work to be done.

EditorData.NodeContext: This rabble - the goblins etc.

Text.Value: I will find you at your camp, and help you with your problem. Right now, I... I need to go be alone.

EditorData.InternalNodeContext: Halsin to go off stage and reappear at the player camp. (New flag needed)
EditorData.NodeContext: Halsin leaves after this to process what's happened. He'll later reappear at the player's campsite.
EditorData.StateChangeTags: Halsin leaves at the end of the node.

Text.Value: Tell me what you know about Moonrise Towers.
Leave.
True, but I mustn't be seen spilling drow blood. Stay here - I'll kill the trio quietly.
Kagha was swayed by Shadow Druids. She nearly sealed the grove.
Pardon the viscera. One should cherish all of nature's bounty... but goblin guts are quite far down the list.

EditorData.InternalNodeContext: Intro happens only once, that's why Global Flag
EditorData.NodeContext: Hint of wry humour, Introducing himself after transforming from an owlbear and killing several goblins.

Text.Value: What's so dangerous about it?
I will help however I can. Let me see to some matters, then I will join you at your camp.
Now, there's no time to lose - get to the grove and help with the defences.
What do you suggest?
This magic isn't typical of how mind flayers procreate?
Three deaths could win us peace: the drow Minthara, the hobgoblin Dror Ragzlin, and that perversion of a priestess, Gut.
I'm sorry to say, I can't undo that magic, which means I can't cure you. But that doesn't mean I can't help.
I'll deal with this. You get to safety.
All right. Wait here until it's done.
Kagha carried out the Rite of Thorns - the grove has been sealed off from the world.
Not so hasty, friend. With the goblins' leaders dead, I can help you. I'll come to your camp, once I've settled some matters.
It is you who should be praised, brother - you are Silvanus' instrument. And please, just Halsin. I will not demand honorifics of my saviour.
It is you who should be praised, sister - you are Silvanus' instrument. And please, just Halsin. I will not demand honorifics of my saviour.
Yes, but just Halsin will suffice. Unbecoming to demand honorifics from the one who saved my hide.

EditorData.NodeContext: Humble and grateful

Text.Value: I already found the place you're talking about - it's called Grymforge.

EditorData.InternalNodeContext: This QN if the player has already entered the grymforge but has not yet spoken to Halsin about it.

Text.Value: One of those who died had a clue that was supposed to help us find the hidden entrance to the Underdark.
Nature's blessings. I thought you'd be on your way by now... unless you changed your mind?

EditorData.logicalname: Player refused to help/Halsin still at GOB

Text.Value: I don't want to risk getting lost in the Underdark - I'll journey overland.
But... something's different. You're aware of the monster inside you. You don't bow to the Absolute, like the True Souls do...

EditorData.NodeContext: The player's in dire straits, but Halsin can't help but be a little fascinated by their condition, Professional interest,

Text.Value: At least I know what to do now. Thank you.
One of the adventurers had a clue to help find it - a dwarf called Brian. It might still be found on his corpse, wherever the goblins left it.
I've been studying these parasites for a while now. Ever since I discovered these so-called True Souls are infected with them.
I must admit, I didn't expect anyone would come to my aid. Who in their right mind would infiltrate a goblin infested temple. Unless...
You ask too much of me. I can't help you.
Farewell. I don't expect we'll meet again - at least not in this life.
Chaos is welcome, in doses; it helps keep balance. But this is too much - this is unnatural.

EditorData.NodeContext: Emphatic. A matter of great importance for him,

Text.Value: The Rite of Thorns...? No.

EditorData.NodeContext: Numb with shock. A catastrophe for Halsin - his home and sacred place of worship is basically lost to him forever.

Text.Value: Tell me what you've learned about the tadpoles' origins.
You're half right - you have to get to Moonrise, but you still have a choice of how to get there.
So be it. May Silvanus lend us nature's fury.

EditorData.NodeContext: Great resolve. Ready to march into battle.

Text.Value: It's too late to stop things from here - the goblins are already marching on the grove in force.
I've already found a way into the Underdark. I can pick up the trail from there.
Death is nature's final slumber - it awaits us all. Do not punish yourself over those lost, or give in to despair - not while there are still folk in need of your help.
I wish I could, but there's still work I've yet to finish - blood I've yet to spill.
Sounds rather ingenious.
The other leaders are dead, but Minthara has left for the grove.
And you'll receive it. I'll make my way to your camp, as soon as I've settled some matters.
It's no coincidence that you found me here, I'll wager? You're after a cure for this parasite.
The decision is yours, but I'd favour the Underdark. Even a place like that is the lesser evil compared to the shadow-cursed lands.
I think you're exaggerating. You just want me to stay and help you.
Let's get out of this pit, firstly.
You are aware you're asking me to kill a drow?
I've got more exploring to do.
Perhaps there's something else I can offer you.
If you can find this place, I'll wager it will reveal a more direct path to Moonrise Towers, and may bypass the worst of the shadow curse.
I may live to regret this - or maybe I won't - but fine, I'll help you save the grove first.

EditorData.logicalname: Refusal to help cancelled if applicable

Text.Value: Patience. I can't just snap my fingers... but I know where the solution almost certainly lies.
Kagha... This is my fault - I was her teacher. I will mourn her when I can.

EditorData.NodeContext: Processing the loss of his understudy, yet he knows she was in the wrong.  He bears no ill will to the player and doesn't have time to truly mourn while his mission is still ongoing

Text.Value: I've explained all that I'm going to. Accept that or I'll give you the same treatment they got.
You're Master Halsin? First Druid of the Emerald Grove? Praise Silvanus for saving you.
You're Halsin? The Master Halsin of the Emerald Grove?

Synopsis: Halsin, arch-druid of the Emerald Grove, is  freed from the goblins and changes back from bear form, thanking the players. They can ask him about their tadpole problem, but he wants help saving the grove first - either by killing the goblin leadership or defending the grove, whichever is applicable. The player can insist on learning what they can from him to help with their tadpole, if they wish.
